<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Section 2.4 - Linear independence</title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>What does it mean for a set of vectors to be linearly dependent? Linearly independent?</p></li>
      <li><p>What is the maximum number of vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m> that can be linearly dependent?</p></li>
      <li><p>When there is a non-trivial solution to the homogeneous equation <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m>, what can you say about the columns of the matrix <m>A</m> (in terms of linear dependence/independence)?</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Consider the matrix
  <md>A =
  \left[
    \begin{array}{ccc}
      3 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
      -1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\
      2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </md>
  whose columns are the vectors <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and <m>\vvec_3</m>.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>[label=(\alph*)]</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.5in">
      <statement>
        <p>Give a parametric description of the solution space to the
    equation <m>A\xvec = \zerovec</m>. (This equation is called ``homogeneous" because of the <m>\zerovec</m>.)</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find one set of nonzero weights <m>c_1</m>, <m>c_2</m>, <m>c_3</m> such that
    <md>
    c_1\vvec_1 + c_2\vvec_2 + c_3\vvec_3 = \zerovec.
    </md></p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Use these weights to show that one of the vectors can be
    written as a linear combination of the others.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Explain why the vectors <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and <m>\vvec_3</m>
    are linearly dependent.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Do the vectors <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and <m>\vvec_3</m> span
    <m>\real^3</m>?  (Hint: Use part (a).)</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>A</m> is any matrix, explain why the homogeneous equation
  <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m> is consistent.  For instance, is there a vector
  you can guarantee is a solution?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What condition on the pivots of <m>A</m> guarantees that there is
  solution to the homogeneous equation <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m> besides the
  solution <m>\xvec=\zerovec</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>In the example above, we saw that having a nonzero solution to
  the homogeneous equation <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m> enabled us to conclude
  that the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly dependent.  What condition on
  the pivots of <m>A</m> will guarantee that the columns of <m>A</m> are
  linearly dependent?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Consider the matrix
  <m>A=
  \left[
    \begin{array}{ccc}
      0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\
      1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m>
  whose columns are <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and <m>\vvec_3</m>.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>[label=(\alph*)]</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Sketch the vectors below.  Do you think the vectors are
    linearly independent or linearly dependent?</p>
        <p>\includegraphics{empty-4.eps}</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Explain how we know that there is a nonzero solution to the
    homogeneous equation <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find a nonzero solution to the homogeneous solution
    <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Use this solution to express one of the vectors as a linear
    combination of the others.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>[label=(\alph*)]</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What condition on the pivots of a matrix <m>A</m> will guarantee that its columns
    are linearly independent?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Suppose that <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\ldots,\vvec_n</m> are linearly
    independent vectors in <m>\real^9</m>.  What can you say about the
    number of vectors in this set?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What is the smallest number of vectors that can span
    <m>\real^{13}</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What is the largest number of vectors in <m>\real^{13}</m> that are
    linearly independent?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Suppose that a set of vectors in <m>\real^{13}</m> is linearly
    independent and spans <m>\real^{13}</m>.  What can you say about the
    number of vectors?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>
